    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-11-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-11-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="1301"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1301">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/29</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-11-07">
                        <hi rend="italic">November 7, 1914</hi>.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>590. Belgian Commission requests that you secure from German Government
                    unmolested passage for neutral food ships from United <pb facs="1130" n="816"
                        xml:id="pg_816"/> States to Holland for Belgium. This has been done by
                    British Government.</p>
                <p>Also inform Department whether German Government has placed embargo on
                    importation into Belgium, in neutral ships, of thoroughly disinfected and
                    cleaned second-hand clothing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
